Why 2 tokens at start?
The reason this matters: you can't invalidate a JWT. Once it's signed, it's valid until it expires. If a user logs out, or you ban an account, the server has no way to force that token to stop working — unless you keep a blacklist. That's why access tokens are kept short-lived. Even if leaked, they expire fast.

NOTE: JWT is encoded (anyone can see it) not encrypted, but if anyone tried to modify in it the server will reject it (403 unauthz error).


The disadv of JWT is the logout:

With sessions, logout is trivial — delete the session row, done. The session ID the user holds becomes meaningless.
With JWT, the token is self-validating. There's no row to delete. So "logout" in JWT typically means:

Frontend logout — React deletes the tokens from localStorage. The user can't make authenticated requests anymore from this device. But technically the token is still valid until expiry.
True logout — add the token to a blacklist in Redis or DB. On every request, check the blacklist. This partially brings back the "DB hit per request" you were trying to avoid with JWT.





























